, with <it>villa</it>, without an inference that there were any dwellings there at all (<it>Catholic Encyclopedia</it> "Gethsemane").</p>

<sec>
<st>
Architecture</st>
<p>

By the first century BC, the "classic" villa took many architectural forms, with many examples employing <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../828/551828.xml">
atrium</link> or <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../857/692857.xml">
peristyle</link>, for enclosed spaces open to light and air.   A villa might be quite palatial, such as the imperial villas built on seaside slopes overlooking the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../490/1104490.xml">
Bay of Naples</link> at <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.8">
<region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
<administrative_district wordnetid="108491826" confidence="0.8">
<location wordnetid="100027167" confidence="0.8">
<tract wordnetid="108673395" confidence="0.8">
<municipality wordnetid="108626283" confidence="0.8">
<geographical_area wordnetid="108574314" confidence="0.8">
<town wordnetid="108665504" confidence="0.8">
<district wordnetid="108552138" confidence="0.8">
<urban_area wordnetid="108675967" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../906/888906.xml">
Baiae</link></urban_area>
</district>
</town>
</geographical_area>
</municipality>
</tract>
</location>
</administrative_district>
</region>
</site>
; others were preserved at <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.8">
<region wordnetid="108630985" confidence="0.8">
<administrative_district wordnetid="108491826" confidence="0.8">
<location wordnetid="100027167" confidence="0.8">
